area_county_sf.name: City and County of San Francisco

area_state_ca_bart.name: San Francisco Bay Area Rapid Transit District
area_state_ca_bart.notes: This district was formed in 1957 and comprises the following counties: Alameda, Contra Costa, and San Francisco.

area_state_ca_courts_of_appeal_d1.name: California Court of Appeal, First District
area_state_ca_courts_of_appeal_d1.notes: This district comprises the following counties: Alameda, Contra Costa, Del Norte, Humboldt, Lake, Marin, Mendocino, Napa, San Francisco, San Mateo, Solano, and Sonoma.

body_ca_board_of_equalization.name: State Board of Equalization
body_ca_board_of_equalization.notes: The State Controller is the fifth member of this body.

body_ca_court_supreme.notes: The Court has six Associate Justices and one Chief Justice. Each is appointed by the Governor and subject to retention elections.

body_ca_courts_of_appeal.notes: This may be better viewed as a type of office rather than a body.

body_ca_courts_of_appeal_d1.notes: This body is divided into five non-geographical divisions with four justices each.

body_sf_college_board.notes: This is also known as the San Francisco Community College Board of Trustees.

body_sf_party_peace_freedom.name: Peace and Freedom County Central Committee

body_sf_superior_court.notes: The Commissioners mentioned by Wikipedia do not face election.

election_method_presidential.name: Presidential Primary
election_method_presidential.notes: There is a Presidential Primary followed by a General Election in November.  The winner in November receives all 55 of California's electoral votes.

election_method_top_two.name: Top-Two Primary
election_method_top_two.notes: All candidates run against each other in a primary election.  Then the top two advance to the general election in November.
